      <hedline>
        <hl1>Equality, Not Tolerance</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan M Dershowitz letter, replying to Aug 31 editorial on Sen Joseph I Lieberman's views on religion in public life, says atheists, agnostics and deists are entitled not to tolerance, but rather to full equality with people of traditional faiths</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Religious Words'' (editorial, Aug. 31):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Religious Words'' (editorial, Aug. 31):</p>
        <p>You extol the virtues of religious ''tolerance.'' Senator Joseph I. Lieberman has also used that term. But tolerance suggests that there is an accepted view that merely tolerates a somewhat less accepted view. It does not imply a full equality.</p>
        <p>In America, atheists, agnostics and deists must be deemed equal to those who adhere to more traditional faiths, not merely tolerated. That was the promise made by George Washington when he wrote the following to the Jewish community of Newport, R.I.: ''It is now no more that toleration is spoken of as it was by the indulgence of one class of people, that another enjoyed the exercise of their inherent natural rights.''</p>
        <p>ALAN M. DERSHOWITZ  New York, Aug. 31, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a visiting scholar at New York University Law School.</p>
      </block>
